        "# Black–76 Learning Notebook\n",
        "\n",
        "This notebook is for learning and experimenting with the **Black–76 model**, which is used for pricing **options on futures** (instead of spot prices like Black–Scholes).\n",
        "\n",
        "We'll:\n",
        "- Import the functions from `black_76.py`\n",
        "- Price a call and a put on a futures contract\n",
        "- Play with the inputs to see how the prices react\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 1. Import the Black–76 functions and price a basic example\n",
        "\n",
        "Here we assume `black_76.py` is in the **same folder** as this notebook.\n",
        "\n",
        "Key inputs:\n",
        "- **F**: current futures price\n",
        "- **K**: strike price of the option\n",
        "- **T**: time to option expiry (in years)\n",
        "- **r**: risk-free interest rate (annual, continuously compounded)\n",
        "- **sigma**: volatility of the futures price (annualized)\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        # Import the call and put pricing functions from black_76.py\n",
        "from black_76 import black_76_call, black_76_put\n",
        "\n",
        "# --- Base example inputs for a futures option ---\n",
        "F = 100.0   # current futures price\n",
        "K = 95.0    # strike price\n",
        "T = 0.75    # time to expiry in years (0.75 = 9 months)\n",
        "r = 0.03    # 3% risk-free rate\n",
        "sigma = 0.20  # 20% volatility of the futures price\n",
        "\n",
        "call_price = black_76_call(F, K, T, r, sigma)\n",
        "put_price  = black_76_put(F, K, T, r, sigma)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Black–76 call price:\", call_price)\n",
        "print(\"Black–76 put price: \", put_price)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 2. Play with the inputs\n",
        "\n",
        "Try editing the values in the cell above and re-running it:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **F** (futures price): what happens if futures are way above or below the strike?\n",
        "- **K** (strike): in-the-money vs at-the-money vs out-of-the-money.\n",
        "- **T** (time): make it very short (0.1) vs longer (2.0).\n",
        "- **r** (rate): higher rates slightly change the discounted factor.\n",
        "- **sigma** (vol): increase volatility and watch option prices increase.\n",
        "\n",
        "This is the main way to build intuition: **change stuff and see what happens**.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 3. See how volatility affects the call price\n",
        "\n",
        "In this cell, we keep everything fixed and only change `sigma`.\n",
        "You should see that higher volatility generally means a more valuable option.\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "from black_76 import black_76_call\n",
        "\n",
        "F = 100.0\n",
        "K = 95.0\n",
        "T = 0.75\n",
        "r = 0.03\n",
        "\n",
        "vol_list = [0.05, 0.10, 0.20, 0.30, 0.50]  # 5% to 50%\n",
        "\n",
        "for sigma in vol_list:\n",
        "    price = black_76_call(F, K, T, r, sigma)\n",
        "    print(f\"sigma = {sigma:.2f}  ->  call price = {price:.4f}\")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 4. Things you can try next\n",
        "\n",
        "- Change **F** and **K** together to see how moneyness affects prices.\n",
        "- Try very small **T** (like 0.01 years) and see prices shrink.\n",
        "- Compare Black–76 vs Black–Scholes in a separate notebook by using:\n",
        "  - Black–Scholes with spot price `S` and dividend yield\n",
        "  - Black–76 with futures price `F`.\n",
        "\n",
        "Use this notebook as a sandbox to build intuition.\n"
      ]
